ew reading of the most notorious massacre in early modern European history rejects most of the established accounts, especially those privileging conspiracy, in favour of an explanation based on ideas of reason of state. The Massacre stimulated reflection on royal power, the limits of authority and obedience, and the danger of religious division for France’s political traditions. Based on extensive research and a careful examination of existing interpretations, this book is the most authoritative analysis of a shattering event.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSaint Bartholomew's Day, Massacre of, France, 1572. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 16th Century.2bisacsh  aEstates general.  aHuguenots.  aReason of state.  aViolence.  aconspiracy.  areligion.1 aBergin, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJouanna, Arlette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611219440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526112194423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526112194/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles